1
00:00:03,800 --> 00:00:07,000
Each run lives in its own git worktree.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,600
That means parallel runs never collide with each other.

3
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:13,800
worca builds on this with two scale-out modes.

4
00:00:13,800 --> 00:00:15,800
The first is fleet mode.

5
00:00:15,800 --> 00:00:21,800
It takes one prompt and runs it across many independent projects at the same time.

6
00:00:21,800 --> 00:00:26,200
That's perfect for rolling a fix across every repo you own.

7
00:00:26,200 --> 00:00:28,200
The second is workspace mode.

8
00:00:28,200 --> 00:00:30,600
This one is for interdependent projects.

9
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:33,800
A master planner figures out the dependency order.

10
00:00:33,800 --> 00:00:36,200
Child pipelines run tier by tier.

11
00:00:36,200 --> 00:00:41,400
And between tiers, worca runs cross-project integration tests to keep everything in sync.

12
00:00:43,200 --> 00:00:47,200
You can shape worca to your team without forking it.

13
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:50,400
Almost every part of a pipeline is configurable.

14
00:00:50,400 --> 00:00:51,600
Which stages run.

15
00:00:51,600 --> 00:00:53,600
Which agent runs each stage.

16
00:00:53,600 --> 00:00:55,600
Which model the agent uses.

17
00:00:55,600 --> 00:00:58,000
How many loop iterations are allowed.

18
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:00,400
Even the prompt the agent sees.

19
00:01:00,400 --> 00:01:02,400
Customization happens at three layers.

20
00:01:02,400 --> 00:01:04,800
The template picks the overall shape.

21
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:06,800
Per-agent overrides tune individual stages.

22
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:13,200
And the guide you attach at run time enforces a spec that nothing else can override.

23
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:18,600
worca ships with a set of built-in pipeline templates.

24
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:21,400
They cover the common shapes of work.

25
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:25,400
There's a full feature pipeline with planning, review, and testing.

26
00:01:25,400 --> 00:01:28,200
There's a bug-fix pipeline that skips planning.

27
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:29,800
There's a docs-only pipeline.

28
00:01:29,800 --> 00:01:31,000
And several more.

29
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:33,400
Each template is a complete recipe.

30
00:01:33,400 --> 00:01:34,200
Stage list.

31
00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:35,000
Agent prompts.

32
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:35,800
Loop budgets.

33
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:36,600
Model assignments.

34
00:01:36,600 --> 00:01:41,400
Most of the time, picking the right template is all you need.

35
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:45,400
When the built-ins don't fit, you can write your own.

36
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:47,800
Today this is done through settings.

37
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:51,400
A richer template-authoring experience is coming to the UI.

38
00:01:53,200 --> 00:01:56,000
The pipeline emits a typed event stream.

39
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,600
There are around 80 different event types in total.

40
00:01:59,600 --> 00:02:00,400
Stage starts.

41
00:02:00,400 --> 00:02:01,200
Bead completions.

42
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:02,000
Test results.

43
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:02,800
Cost ticks.

44
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:03,600
Control decisions.

45
00:02:03,600 --> 00:02:06,400
You subscribe to these events through webhooks.

46
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:08,800
The webhooks are signed for security.

47
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:11,200
Some subscribers can also push back.

48
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:18,000
Control webhooks let you pause, resume, stop, or override a decision while the run is in flight.

49
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:22,000
The UI itself is just one subscriber to this stream.

50
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:28,000
That's why everything you see in the UI is also available to your own tools.

51
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:35,000
worca can push run updates into the chat tools your team already uses.

52
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Set up an integration once.

53
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,800
That can be Telegram, Discord, or Slack.

54
00:02:39,800 --> 00:02:43,800
From then on, worca notifies you when something interesting happens.

55
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:45,400
A plan is ready.

56
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:47,800
A pull request has been opened.

57
00:02:47,800 --> 00:02:49,400
The run has paused.

58
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:51,000
A circuit breaker tripped.

59
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:54,200
On Telegram, those notifications come with inline actions.

60
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:59,000
You can pause, resume, or stop a run right from the chat.

61
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,400
No need to open the UI.

62
00:03:01,400 --> 00:03:07,800
And from inside a run, agents can reach out to you directly through the notify skill.

63
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:20,200
For example, an agent might say: "I'm waiting on a clarification, please reply when you can." You can leave the UI closed and still stay in the loop on long-running work.
